 <p><span id="docs-internal-guid-a6de0e9f-41f4-172e-ec39-18ef9e51af22"><br /><span>Just today, I finished reading a Signet Classic by George Orwell by the name of </span><span>Animal Farm. </span><span>It was an incredibly interesting book, but the thing about it was it kept getting more and more sad. It reminded me of the human trait that has taken its roots deep within us. Greed. Even ancient people were aware of this trait. Their myth of how humans got to be like this is called Pandora. Summing it up, Pandora wants to see what is inside of a box that she was told not to open, so she opens it. Various ugly monsters emerge from the box, all representing a negative human trait. &nbsp;If you got bit by one of the monsters, you would end up having that trait. It turns out that eventually, everyone gets bitten and passes the traits through eons of generations. One of the monsters was named Greed. </span></span></p><p dir="ltr"><span><span class="Apple-tab-span"> </span></span><span>Old Major, a Middle prize bull calls the animals to a meeting one night after Mr. Jones, the owner of the farm has gone to bed drunk and confused. &ldquo;Old Major was so highly regarded on the farm that everyone was willing to lose an hours&rsquo; sleep to hear what he had to say.&rdquo; (pg. 4)</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>He says that he is getting old and that he wants to share with them a small spark of hope to carry on through generations. A Rebellion. &ldquo;The life of an animal is misery and slavery: that is plain truth.&rdquo; (pg. 7)</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>He makes it clear that when the rebellion starts, the animals must not have anything to do with humans and must equal and not kill. </span></p>
<p><span><span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>Three days later, Old Major dies peacefully in his sleep, as warned during his speech. The animals were so excited about the rebellion that they overthrew the farm shortly after. They make 7 sacred rules that all animals must follow called the Seven Commandments. Here they are:</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>Whatever goes upon two legs is an enemy.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>Whatever goes upon four legs or has wings is a friend</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>No animal shall sleep in a bed.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>No animal shall wear clothes.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>No animal shall drink alcohol.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>No animal shall kill another animal.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>All animals are equal.</span></p>
<p><span><span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>The animals all agreed on this and chose the pigs to be leaders, owing to the fact that they are the smartest and can read. Life goes on and the animals are all content, but the pigs start to do little acts of luxury such as taking milk and apples for themselves to &ldquo;preserve their health. The acts start getting more outrageous though and all of a sudden the pigs are breaking the Commandments (and changing them) left and right. But the animals think that since the pigs are smart, they must be doing it for a good reason and nobody rebels. By the end of the book almost all of the Commandments were either broken or changed by the pigs. </span></p>
<p><span><span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<ol>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr"><span>Whatever goes upon two legs is an enemy.</span></p>
