<p dir="ltr"><span>3. No animal shall sleep in a bed </span><span>with sheets.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>CHANGED AND BROKEN</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>The pigs &nbsp;took off the sheets and used blankets as to not break the tweaked rule.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>4. No animal shall wear clothes.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>5. No animal shall drink alcohol.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>BROKEN</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>The pigs were caught by the other animals drinking in the dead of night.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>6. No animal shall kill another animal </span><span>for no reason.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>CHANGED AND BROKEN</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>There was an incredibly large execution where dozens of animals were killed for very minor crimes by the nine dogs who ripped their throats out.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>7. All animals are equal </span><span>but some are more equal than others.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>CHANGED AND BROKEN</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>At this point, it&rsquo;s kind of obvious why it was broken.</span></p>
<p><span><span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>On the other side of the wall of Commandments, there was also a poem talking about how great Napoleon (the leader pig) was.</span></p>
<p><span><span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>But although the whole book got continuously more sad, the last part was what made me almost burst into tears. The pigs met up with some human farmers to eat dinner, drink and talk about the pig&rsquo;s farming tactics. These were the very last words of the book:</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>&ldquo;The animals outside looked from pig to man, man to pig again; but already it was impossible to tell which was which.&rdquo; (pg. 141)</span></p>
<p><span><span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><span>~Jeremy</span></p>
